<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> "...For him, pulsation and tonality were not just cultural artifacts. They were the lifeblood of the musical experience, natural laws. It was his triumph to find a way to embrace these fundamental principles and still create a music that felt genuine and new. He didn't reinvent the wheel so much as he showed us a new way to ride." See for instance, <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://rgable.typepad.com/aworks/2004/08/come_out_steve_.html" class="external text" title="http://rgable.typepad.com/aworks/2004/08/come_out_steve_.html" rel="nofollow">""New" American classical music"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://rgable.typepad.com/aworks/2004/08/come_out_steve_.html" class="external free" title="http://rgable.typepad.com/aworks/2004/08/come_out_steve_.html" rel="nofollow">http://rgable.typepad.com/aworks/2004/08/come_out_steve_.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2006-10-25</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=%22New%22+American+classical+music&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Frgable.typepad.com%2Faworks%2F2004%2F08%2Fcome_out_steve_.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Steve_Reich"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
